value.value: The dorsal-most lateral acute muscle of the prothoracic segment.
The second dorsal-most lateral acute muscle of the prothoracic segment.
Any intersegmental muscle (FBbt:00058311) that overlaps some larval prothoracic segment (FBbt:00001743).

Ventrally located larval hypodermal muscle that belongs to a large bundle of five fibers spanning the thoracic segments (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). They span at least the prothoracic segment (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997), with some fibers attaching to the mouthparts anteriorly (Matthes et al., 1995) and one fiber (VIS5) reaches the apodeme between T3 and A1 posteriorly (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

definition.value: Hooper (1986) - FBrf0044229 shows all of these extending to at least T2-T3 in third instar.

value.value: Second dorsal-most ventral intersegmental muscle attached to the anterior apodeme of the prothoracic segment. Its posterior end is attached to the T1-T2 intersegmental apodeme (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

Third dorsal-most ventral intersegmental muscle attached to the anterior apodeme of the prothoracic segment. Its posterior end is attached to the T1-T2 intersegmental apodeme (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

Fourth dorsal-most ventral intersegmental muscle attached to the anterior apodeme of the prothoracic segment. Its posterior end is attached to the T1-T2 intersegmental apodeme (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
The most ventral of the larval ventral intersegmental muscles. It stretches from the anterior prothoracic segment to the T3-A1 apodeme (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997; Hartenstein, 2006).
Any embryonic/larval hypodermal muscle (FBbt:00058298) that is part of some mesothoracic segment (FBbt:00000018).
Larval acute muscle of the mesothoracic segment (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). There are four of these on each side, all found in a dorsal position (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
